df_icon=\nshow_print_icon=\nshow_email_icon=\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=', 8, 0, 1, '', '', 0, 5611, 'robots=\nauthor='),
(11, 'November 2008', 'november2008', '', '<h2 class="TopItem"><a href="#"  name="news01" id="news01"></a><a href="http://www.kaiseisha.net/author/nahoko_uehashi.html">Nahoko Uehashi</a> and <a href="http://www.kaiseisha.net/author/katsumi_komagata.html">Katsumi Komagata</a> nominated for Astrid Lindgren Memorial Award 2009</a></h2>\r\n<p class="Date">November 2008</p>\r\n<p>Since 2003, the Astrid Lindgren Memorial Award has been awarded annually to those at the very forefront of the world of children''s fiction, such as Maurice Sendak, Philip Pullman, and, in 2005, Japan''s own <a href="http://www.kaiseisha.net/author/ryoji_arai.html">Ryoji Arai</a>. Now, two Japanese children''s authors, <a href="http://www.kaiseisha.net/author/nahoko_uehashi.html">Nahoko Uehashi</a> and<a href="http://www.kaiseisha.net/author/katsumi_komagata.html">Katsumi Komagata</a>, have been listed amongst the nominees for the 2009 award. With her Moribito (Guardian) series published in countries all around the world, author <a href="http://www.kaiseisha.net/author/nahoko_uehashi.html">Nahoko Uehashi</a> is active internationally and was invited this August to attend the Berlin International Literature Festival.<a href="http://www.kaiseisha.net/author/katsumi_komagata.html">Katsumi Komagata</a> is internationally renowned as a bookmaker, artist and designer, giving frequent workshops in countries such as France, Switzerland and Korea, and working as a judge at the Bologna Book Fair. We are delighted that Japan''s forerunning writers should have been selected as nominees for such a prestigious award. The winner of the award, to be chosen from a list of around 150 nominees, is due to be announced in March of next year. </p>\r\n<table border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0"><tr><td><a href="http://www.kaiseisha.net/staging/backlist/fiction/title/481.html"><img src="http://www.kaiseisha.net/staging/images/news/nov2008/moribito_01.jpg" alt="MORIBITO (Guardian) series by Nahoko Uehashi illus. by Makiko Futaki" /></a><a href="http://www.kaiseisha.net/staging/backlist/fiction/title/479.html"><img src="http://www.kaiseisha.net/staging/images/news/nov2008/moribito_02.jpg" alt="MORIBITO (Guardian) series by Nahoko Uehashi illus. by Makiko Futaki" style="margin-left:4px;" /></a></td>\r\n<td valign="bottom" style="padding-left:20px;"><a href="http://www.kaiseisha.net/staging/backlist/picture/title/580.html"><img src="http://www.kaiseisha.net/staging/images/news/nov2008/littleeye_01.jpg" alt="LITTLE EYES series by Katsumi Komagata" /></a><a href="http://www.kaiseisha.net/staging/backlist/picture/title/581.html"><img src="http://www.kaiseisha.net/staging/images/news/nov2008/littleeye_02.jpg" alt="LITTLE EYES series by Katsumi Komagata" style="margin:0 3px;" /></a><a href="http://www.kaiseisha.net/staging/backlist/picture/title/582.html"><img src="http://www.kaiseisha.net/staging/images/news/nov2008/littleeye_03.jpg" alt="LITTLE EYES series by Katsumi Komagata" /></a></td>\r\n</tr><tr><td class="NewsBookDescription" valign="top"><span class="NewsBookTitle">MORIBITO (Guardian) series</span><br />\r\n by Nahoko Uehashi, illus. by Makiko Futaki</td><td class="NewsBookDescription" valign="top" style="padding-left:20px;"><span class="NewsBookTitle">LITTLE EYES series</span> by Katsumi Komagata</span></td></tr></table>\r\n<h2><a name="news02" id="news02"></a><a href="http://www.kaiseisha.net/staging/newpublications/newpicture/title/570.html">''The Sun Organ''</a> Goes On Sale!</h2>\r\n<p class="Date">November 2008</p>\r\n<p>After announcing the publication of <a href="http://www.kaiseisha.net/author/ryoji_arai.html">Ryoji Arai</a>''s <a href="http://www.kaiseisha.net/staging/newpublications/newpicture/title/570.html">''The Sun Organ''</a> in our previous news update, we are pleased to announce that the volume is now on sale. The book, which was originally published by Artone in 2007, has now been published by Kaisei-sha. <a href="http://www.kaiseisha.net/staging/newpublications/newpicture/title/570.html">''The Sun Organ''</a> is considered by many to be the finest work of children''s author <a href="http://www.kaiseisha.net/author/ryoji_arai.html">Ryoji Arai</a>, a previous winner of the Astrid Lindgren Memorial Award mentioned above. The book, which tells of the journey of the Elephant Bus as it goes down a mountain, crosses a huge bridge, goes into a town and picks up people before crossing the sea on a boat and passing through the desert, is characterized by Arai''s utterly original tempo and use of colour. The book was the winner of the 2007 1st JBBY (Japanese Board on Books for Young People) award and placed on the Honour List of the 2008 IBBY (International Board on Books for Young People) Award. </p>\r\n<p><a href="http://www.kaiseisha.net/author/ryoji_arai.html">Click here</a> to see other books by Ryoji Arai</p>\r\n<table cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" border="0"><tr><td colspan="2"><a href="http://www.kaiseisha.net/staging/newpublications/newpicture/title/570.html"><img src="http://www.kaiseisha.net/staging/images/news/nov2008/taiyo-organ1.jpg" alt="The Sun Organ" style="margin-right:5px;" /></a>\r\n<img src="http://www.kaiseisha.net/staging/images/news/nov2008/taiyo-organ2.jpg" alt="The Sun Organ" /></td></tr>\r\n<tr><td><span class="NewsBookDescription"><span class="New">NEW!</span><span class="NewsBookTitle"> The Sun Organ</span>by Ryoji Arai<br />\r\n22 x 31 cm,  32 pages, Full-colour illustrations</span></td><td style="text-align:right; vertical-align:top;">&copy;Ryoji Arai</td></tr></table>\r\n<h2><a name="news03" id="news03"></a>Have you discovered <a href="http://www.kaiseisha.net/author/jun_okada.html">Jun Okada</a> yet?</h2>\r\n<p class="Date">November 2008</p>\r\n<div style="float:right; text-align:right; margin-left:8px;"><a href="http://www.kaiseisha.net/staging/newpublications/fiction/title/575.html"><img src="http://www.kaiseisha.net/staging/images/news/nov2008/funguri-konguri.jpg" alt="Funguri Konguri" /></a><br />\r\n<span class="NewsBookDescription"><span class="New">NEW! </span><span class="NewsBookTitle">Funguri Konguri – Storytelling in the Art Class</span><br />\r\n22 x 16 cm,  164 pages, Black-and-white illustrations</span></div>\r\n<p><a href="http://www.kaiseisha.net/author/jun_okada.html">Jun Okada</a>''s works of fantasy, set in schools, were penned whilst the author was working as a primary school teacher. Highly esteemed across Asia, Okada''s books are published widely in countries such as Korea, Taiwan and Thailand. Having also worked as an art teacher, most of Okada''s work features his own illustrations. Since his retirement from teaching last year, Okada has been dedicating himself to his writing, and October of this year saw the publication of his first work in many years, <a href="http://www.kaiseisha.net/staging/newpublications/fiction/title/575.html">''Funguri Konguri''</a>. This exciting new volume is a collection of six heart-warming stories told by an art teacher to some rather unusual guests who come to visit the art room.<br /></p>\r\n<p style="clear:both;"><a href="http://www.kaiseisha.net/author/jun_okada.html">Click here</a> to see other books by Jun Okada</p>', '', 1, 1, 0, 1, '2008-11-13 19:13:24', 62, '', '2009-02-02 15:20:54', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2008-11-13 19:13:24', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', 'show_title=\nlink_titles=\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=\nshow_create_date=\nshow_modify_date=\nshow_pdf_icon=\nshow_print_icon=\nshow_email_icon=\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=', 27, 0, 26, '', '', 0, 1564, 'robots=\nauthor=');
