(12, 'February 2009', 'february2009', '', '<!-- contents sterts -->\r\n\r\n<h2 class="TopItem"><a name="news01" id="news01"></a><a href="http://www.kaiseisha.net/backlist/fiction/title/479.html">MORIBITO: Guardian of the Spirit</a> wins The Mildred L. Batchelder Award 2009</h2>\r\n<p class="Date">February 2009</p>\r\n<div style="width:220px; float:left; padding-bottom:25px;"><a href="http://www.kaiseisha.net/backlist/fiction/title/479.html"><img src="images/news/feb2009/moribito.jpg" alt="MORIBITO: Guardian of the Spirit" border="0" /></a><br />\r\n<span class="NewsBookDescription"><span class="NewsBookTitle">MORIBITO (Guardian)<br />\r\nGuardian of the Spirit</span><br />\r\nby Nahoko Uehashi, illus. by Makiko Futaki\r\n</span>\r\n</div>\r\n<p>On 27th January 2009, the English translation of <a href="http://www.kaiseisha.net/backlist/fiction/title/479.html">MORIBITO: Guardian of the Spirit</a>, published in the US in 2008, was announced as the winner of The Mildred A. Batchelder Award 2009. The book was written by <a href="http://www.kaiseisha.net/author/nahoko_uehashi.html">Nahoko Uehashi</a>, translated by Cathy Hirano, and published by Arthur A. Levine Books. \r\nThe Mildred L. Batchelder Award is given each year by the American Library Association to honour the most outstanding children’s book originally published in a foreign language and translated into English and published in the United States. \r\nIn addition to English, translated versions are also scheduled to be published in Taiwan, Italy and Brazil. We hope that the award will highlight the innovative talent to be found in the Kaisei-sha catalogue. </p>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<!--//end of 1 //-->\r\n\r\n<h2 class="Clear"><a name="news02" id="news02"></a>Kaisei-sha to exhibit at the Bologna Children’s Book Fair 2009</h2>\r\n<p class="Date">February 2009</p>\r\n<div style="float:left; width:238px; padding-bottom:25px;">\r\n<img src="images/news/feb2009/bologna.jpg" alt="the Bologna Children’s Book Fair 2009" />\r\n</div>\r\n<p>Kaisei-sha is delighted to be once again visiting the Bologna Children’s Book Fair, to be held in Bologna in Italy between 23rd and 26th March 2009. We are planning to showcase our new publications, made available since the 2008 Fair, and we hope it will be a chance to greet friends both old and new. We’ll be waiting to welcome you at Stall A-18 in Hall 29. </p>\r\n\r\n<!--//end of 2 //-->\r\n\r\n\r\n<h2 class="Clear"><a name="news03" id="news03"></a>A new title from much-loved <a href="http://www.kaiseisha.net/illustrator/satomi_ichikawa.html">Satomi Ichikawa</a></h2>\r\n<p class="Date">February 2009</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href="http://www.kaiseisha.net/newpublications/newpicture/title/612.html">The Town Has Disappeared</a> is the long-awaited new title from <a href="http://www.kaiseisha.net/illustrator/satomi_ichikawa.html">Satomi Ichikawa</a>, a Japanese illustrator who lives in France and whose pictures have enchanted children across the globe.\r\nThis new title sees her working once again with <a href="http://www.kaiseisha.net/author/eiko_kadono.html">Eiko Kadono</a>, one of the most respected writers of children’s literature today. \r\nA granny and her cat are living in a grey and dark house. But, using their imagination, they fill the house with gardens and birds and ice-cream parlours. Then, one day, everything that they have imagined together comes true. \r\nIchikawa uses her characteristically delicate touch to conjure up the granny’s humble lifestyle. The pair have previously worked together on <a href="http://www.kaiseisha.net/backlist/picture/title/115.html">Dumpling Soup</a>, also published by Kaisei-sha.  \r\n</p>\r\n<table border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0">\r\n  <tr>\r\n    <td><a href="http://www.kaiseisha.net/newpublications/newpicture/title/612.html"><img src="images/news/feb2009/the_town_has_disappeared02.jpg" width="210" height="260" border="0" /></a></td>\r\n    <td style="padding-left:30px;"><a href="http://www.kaiseisha.net/backlist/picture/title/115.html"><img src="images/news/feb2009/odango_soup.jpg" width="160" height="195" style="margin-top:65px;" border="0" /></a></td>\r\n  </tr>\r\n  <tr>\r\n    <td><span class="NewsBookDescription"><span class="New">NEW!</span><span class="NewsBookTitle">The Town Has Disappeared</span><br />\r\nby Eiko Kadono, illus. by Satomi Ichikawa<br />\r\n26 x 22 cm, 32 pages, Full-colour illustrations</span></td>\r\n    <td style="padding-left:30px;"><span class="NewsBookDescription"><span class="NewsBookTitle">Dumpling Soup</span><br />\r\nby Eiko Kadono, illus. by Satomi Ichikawa</span>\r\n</td>\r\n  </tr>\r\n<tr><td colspan="2">&nbsp;</td></tr>\r\n<tr><td colspan="2"><a href="http://www.kaiseisha.net/newpublications/newpicture/title/612.html"><img src="images/news/feb2009/the_town_has_disappeared01.jpg" width="408" height="303" alt="The Town Has Disappeared" border="0" /></a></td></tr>\r\n\r\n</table>\r\n<!--//end of 3 //-->\r\n<h2><a name="news04" id="news04"></a>A new title is added to <a href="http://www.kaiseisha.net/author/masayuki_sebe.html">Masayuki Sebe</a>’s popular series</h2>\r\n<p class="Date">February 2009</p>\r\n<p><a href="http://www.kaiseisha.net/author/masayuki_sebe.html">Masayuki Sebe</a>’s <strong>100 Play Hide-and-Seek</strong>, the follow-up to the popular <a href="http://www.kaiseisha.net/backlist/picture/title/519.html">100 in Total</a> and <a href="http://www.kaiseisha.net/backlist/picture/title/616.html">Dinosaur Puzzles</a>, which proved such a hit at both the Bologna and Frankfurt Book Fairs in 2008 and for which the rights have already been sold in France and Taiwan, will be published in March 2009. \r\nPirates, Santa Claus, marathon runners, children...there are 217 items in total for the reader to find, with each spread featuring 100 colourful characters.\r\n</p>\r\n<table border="0">\r\n  <tr>\r\n    <td><img src="images/news/feb2009/hide_and_seek.jpg" alt="100 Play Hide-and-Seek" width="200" height="245" /></td>\r\n    <td style="padding:55px 10px 0 10px;"><a href="http://www.kaiseisha.net/backlist/picture/title/519.html"><img src="images/news/feb2009/zenbude_100.jpg" alt="100 in Total" width="160" height="190" border="0" /></a></td>\r\n    <td style="padding-top:55px;"><a href="http://www.kaiseisha.net/backlist/picture/title/616.html"><img src="images/news/feb2009/puzzle.jpg" alt="Dinosaur Puzzles" width="160" height="190" border="0" /></a></td>\r\n  </tr>\r\n  <tr>\r\n    <td><span class="NewsBookDescription"><span class="NewsBookTitle">100 Play Hide-and-Seek</span></span><br />\r\n *Provisional image</td>\r\n    <td style="padding:0 10px;"><span class="NewsBookDescription"><span class="NewsBookTitle">100 in Total</span><br /> by Masayuki Sebe</span></td>\r\n    <td><span class="NewsBookDescription"><span class="NewsBookTitle">Dinosaur Puzzles</span><br />\r\nby Masayuki Sebe</span></td>\r\n  </tr>\r\n</table>\r\n<!--//end of 4 //-->\r\n\r\n<h2><a name="news05" id="news05"></a>Two new travel books for adults published</h2>\r\n<p class="Date">February 2009</p>\r\n<p>Kaisei-sha has published two new travel books that will appeal to readers of all ages from Junior High students and upwards.<a href="http://www.kaiseisha.net/newpublications/newpicture/title/607.html"> Mexico, Mole Country</a> is by the contemporary artist Junko Mada. This colourful, engaging tale of Junko’s travels to Mexico’s ancient ruins and art galleries is full of her original artwork and photography. \r\n<a href="http://www.kaiseisha.net/newpublications/newpicture/title/606.html">Wi’ la’ mola</a> is a true-life story of the life the author shared, during her time travelling around Canada, with Wolfy the half-wolf puppy. Together they travel, grow and learn. The book charms the reader with gorgeous photographs of the Canadian countryside, and heart-warming tales of the kindness of the people they meet. </p>\r\n<table border="0">\r\n  <tr>\r\n    <td><a href="http://www.kaiseisha.net/newpublications/nonfiction/title/607.html"><img src="images/news/feb2009/mexico.jpg" alt="Mexico, Mole Country" width="180" height="250" border="0"></a></td>\r\n    <td style="padding-left:20px;"><a href="http://www.kaiseisha.net/newpublications/nonfiction/title/606.html"><img src="images/news/feb2009/wilamora.jpg" alt="Wi’ la’ mola: My Travels with Wolfy the Wolf Puppy" width="180" height="250" border="0" /></a></td>\r\n  </tr>\r\n  <tr>\r\n    <td><span class="NewsBookDescription"><span class="New">NEW!</span><span class="NewsBookTitle">Mexico, Mole Country</span><br />\r\nby Junko Mada, 21 x 15 cm, 176 pages<br />\r\nFull-colour photographs and illustrations</span>\r\n</td>\r\n    <td style="padding-left:20px;"><span class="NewsBookDescription"><span class="New">NEW!</span><span class="NewsBookTitle">Wi’ la’ mola: My Travels with Wolfy the Wolf-dog Puppy</span><br />\r\nby Chie Tanaka<br />\r\n21 x 15 cm, 259 pages, Full-colour photographs</span>\r\n</td>\r\n  </tr>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n\r\n<!--//end of 5 //-->\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<!--//contents ends-->', '', 1, 1, 0, 1, '2009-02-02 18:32:15', 62, '', '2009-03-19 17:13:09', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2009-02-02 18:32:15', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', 'show_title=\nlink_titles=\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=\nshow_create_date=\nshow_modify_date=\nshow_pdf_icon=\nshow_print_icon=\nshow_email_icon=\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=', 15, 0, 29, '', '', 0, 675, 'robots=\nauthor='),
(13, 'TEST-Homepage', 'testhomepage', '', '<div class="Left">\r\n          <div class="TitleRow">\r\n            <h2><a href="http://www.kaiseisha.net/staging/news.html">NEWS</a></h2>\r\n            <div class="Navigation">| <a href="http://www.kaiseisha.net/staging/news.html">Latest</a> | <a href="http://www.kaiseisha.net/staging/news/archive.html">Archive</a> | <span class="Highlight">November 2008 updated</span> |</div>\r\n            <div class="Clear"></div>\r\n          </div>\r\n          <p><a href="index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=11&Itemid=2#news01">Nahoko Uehashi and Katsumi Komagata nominated for Astrid Lindgren Memorial Award 2009</a></p>\r\n          <p class="Lined"><a href="index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=11&Itemid=2#news02">''The Sun Organ'' Goes On Sale!</a></p>\r\n          <p class="Lined"><a href="index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=11&Itemid=2#news03">Have you discovered Jun Okada yet?</a></p>\r\n          \r\n        </div>\r\n        <div class="Right">\r\n          <div class="TitleRow">\r\n            <h2><a href="http://www.kaiseisha.net/staging/about.html">ABOUT US</a></h2>\r\n            <div class="Navigation">| <a href="http://www.kaiseisha.net/about/index.html">History</a> | <a href="http://www.kaiseisha.net/about/foreign.html">Foreign Titles</a> | <a href="http://www.kaiseisha.net/staging/about/internationalawards.html">International Awards</a> |</div>\r\n            <div class="Clear"></div>\r\n          </div>\r\n          <a href="http://www.kaiseisha.net/about/index.html">\r\n          <p>KAISEI-SHA was founded in 1936, and specializes in the publication of children''s books in all fields, including picture books, fiction and non-fiction.</p>\r\n          <p>About 3,000 titles are currently available, including some 1,200 translations. More than 100 new titles are published annually, and at present foreign editions of our books exceed 1,000 titles....</p>\r\n          <p>read more</p>\r\n          </a> </div>', '', 1, 0, 0, 0, '2009-02-05 14:28:08', 62, '', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 0, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2009-02-05 14:28:08', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', 'show_title=\nlink_titles=\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=\nshow_create_date=\nshow_modify_date=\nshow_pdf_icon=\nshow_print_icon=\nshow_email_icon=\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=', 1, 0, 1, '', '', 0, 2, 'robots=\nauthor='),
(14, 'May 2009', 'may2009', '', '<h2 class="TopItem"><a name="news01" id="news01"></a>2009 Bologna Book Fair visit</h2>\r\n<p class="Date">May 2009</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Once again, Kaisei-sha exhibited at the Bologna Children’s Book Fair, which was held in Bologna, Italy between 23rd and 26th March 2009. We were delighted to welcome many visitors to our stand, and to see the interest shown in Japanese books by so many of the international guests. Particularly popular this year were <a href="http://www.kaiseisha.net/newpublications/newpicture/title/624.html">Hide and Seek by 100</a>, <a href="http://www.kaiseisha.net/newpublications/newpicture/title/622.html">Fridge</a>, <a href="http://www.kaiseisha.net/newpublications/newpicture/title/623.html">Closet</a> and <a href="http://www.kaiseisha.net/backlist/fiction/title/110.html">I’m an African Giraffe</a>. We would like to thank everyone who came to visit us, and we hope to see you again next year. </p>\r\n\r\n<p><img src="images/news/may2009/bologna01.jpg" alt="2009 Bologna Book Fair visit" style="margin:0 20px 26px 0;" />\r\n<img src="images/news/may2009/bologna02.jpg" alt="2009 Bologna Book Fair visit" /></p>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<!--//end of 1 //-->\r\n\r\n<h2 class="Clear"><a name="news02" id="news02"></a><a href="http://www.kaiseisha.net/backlist/fiction/title/479.html">MORIBITO: Guardian of the Spirit</a> makes its debut at Bologna</h2>\r\n<p class="Date">May 2009</p>\r\n<p>The Italian translation of <a href="http://www.kaiseisha.net/backlist/fiction/title/479.html">MORIBITO: Guardian of the Spirit</a>, by <a href="http://www.kaiseisha.net/author/nahoko_uehashi.html">Nahoko Uehashi</a>, made was debuted at the Bologna Book Fair. The book is so far scheduled to be translated into a total of six languages. In Italy, the translation will be published by Salani Editore, which also publishes the Harry Potter series, and works by respected children’s authors such as Michael Ende and Philip Pullman. The book is being presented with an impressive, imposing black-themed cover, with the text presented beautifully. We hope that the translation will prove as popular in Italy as the original has done in Japan. </p>\r\n<p><img src="images/news/may2009/moribito01.jpg" alt="2009 Bologna Book Fair visit" style="margin-right:20px;" />\r\n<img src="images/news/may2009/moribito02.jpg" alt="2009 Bologna Book Fair visit" /></p>\r\n<!--//end of 2 //-->\r\n\r\n\r\n<h2 class="Clear"><a name="news03" id="news03"></a>New baby books are a sell-out success</h2>\r\n<p class="Date">May 2009</p>\r\n<div style="float:left; margin-right:10px;"><a href="http://www.kaiseisha.net/newpublications/newpicture/title/622.html"><img src="images/news/may2009/fridge.jpg" alt="Fridge" /></a><br />\r\n<span class="NewsBookDescription"><span class="New">NEW!</span><span class="NewsBookTitle">Fridge</span><br />\r\nby Hiroyuki Arai<br />\r\n18 x 13 cm, 19 pages, Full-colour illustrations</span></div>\r\n<p>Although only released in April, our first print runs of <a href="http://www.kaiseisha.net/newpublications/newpicture/title/622.html">Fridge</a> and <a href="http://www.kaiseisha.net/newpublications/newpicture/title/623.html">Closet</a> have already sold out, within less than a month, and are now set for a reprint. These charming board books are designed to look like a real fridge and Closet; as the pages are turned, babies will come across the kind of items that are really kept in these places – milk, strawberries and eggs in the fridge, and blankets and pillows in the Closet. And these two books are just the first of a series planned around the theme of ‘storage’. Look out for the new editions as they are published!   \r\n</p>\r\n\r\n<table border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" class="Clear" style="margin-top:10px;">\r\n  <tr>\r\n    <td><a href="http://www.kaiseisha.net/newpublications/newpicture/title/623.html"><img src="images/news/may2009/cupboard01.jpg" width="373" height="270" border="0" alt="Closet" /></a></td>\r\n    <td style="padding-left:30px;"><a href="http://www.kaiseisha.net/newpublications/newpicture/title/623.html"><img src="images/news/may2009/cupboard02.jpg" width="169" height="243" border="0" alt="Closet" /></a></td>\r\n  </tr>\r\n  <tr>\r\n<td colspan="2"><span class="NewsBookDescription"><span class="New">NEW!</span><span class="NewsBookTitle">Closet</span><br />\r\nby Hiroyuki Arai<br />\r\n18 x 13 cm, 19 pages, Full-colour illustrations</span></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</table>\r\n<!--//end of 3 //-->\r\n<h2><a name="news04" id="news04"></a><a href="http://www.kaiseisha.net/author/mitsuhiko_imamori.html">Mitsuhiko Imamori</a> wins the prestigious Domon Ken Award </h2>\r\n<p class="Date">May 2009</p>\r\n<p><a href="http://www.kaiseisha.net/author/mitsuhiko_imamori.html">Mitsuhiko Imamori</a>, a photographer who specialises in taking pictures of insects, has been announced as the winner of the 28th Domon Ken Award. This award is one of Japan’s two most prestigious photography awards, and is presented to photographers who have excelled in the field of documentary photography, such as society, people and the natural world. Kaisei-sha currently publishes three books featuring Imamori’s stunning photography. \r\n</p>\r\n<table border="0">\r\n  <tr>\r\n    <td style="padding-right:15px; width:191px;"><a href="http://www.kaiseisha.net/backlist/nonfiction/title/103.html"><img src="images/news/may2009/mitsuhikoImamori01.jpg" alt="The Old Fisherman who Smelt of Water" border="0" /></a></td>\r\n    <td style="padding-right:15px; width:174px;"><a href="http://www.kaiseisha.net/backlist/nonfiction/title/104.html"><img src="images/news/may2009/mitsuhikoImamori02.jpg" alt="The Old Fisherman who Smelt of Water" border="0" /></a></td>\r\n    <td style=" width:174px; vertical-align:text-top;"><a href="http://www.kaiseisha.net/backlist/nonfiction/title/626.html"><img src="images/news/may2009/mitsuhikoImamori03.jpg" alt="The landscape of Satoyama" border="0" /></a></td>\r\n  </tr>\r\n  <tr>\r\n    <td style="vertical-align:text-top;"><span class="NewsBookDescription"><span class="NewsBookTitle">The Old Fisherman who Smelt of Water</span><br />\r\nby Mitsuhiko Imamori<br />\r\n27 x 23 cm, 64 pages<br />\r\nFull-colour photographs</span></td>\r\n    <td><span class="NewsBookDescription"><span class="NewsBookTitle"> A Journey to Encounter Wonderful Lives</span><br />by Mitsuhiko Imamori<br />\r\n25 x 20 cm, 40 pages<br />\r\nFull-colour photographs</span></td>\r\n    <td style="vertical-align:text-top;"><span class="NewsBookDescription"><span class="New">NEW!</span><span class="NewsBookTitle">The landscape of Satoyama</span><br />\r\nby Mitsuhiko Imamori<br />\r\n26 x 19 cm, 94 pages<br />\r\nFull-colour photographs</span></td>\r\n  </tr>\r\n</table>\r\n<!--//end of 4 //-->', '', 1, 1, 0, 1, '2009-05-26 10:16:15', 62, '', '2009-05-28 09:14:05', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2009-05-26 10:16:15', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', 'show_title=\nlink_titles=\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=\nshow_create_date=\nshow_modify_date=\nshow_pdf_icon=\nshow_print_icon=\nshow_email_icon=\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=', 4, 0, 27, '', '', 0, 603, 'robots=\nauthor='),
(15, 'August 2009', 'august2009', '', '<h2 class="TopItem"><a name="news01" id="news01"></a><a href="http://kaiseisha.net/overseas/fiction/country/title/479.html?country=13">"MORIBITO II: Guardian of the Darkness"</a>: Starred Review on Publishers Weekly!</h2>\r\n<p class="Date">August 2009</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="float:left; width:400px;">Following on from the success of MORIBITO: Guardian of the Spirit, the English translation of MORIBITO II: Guardian of the Darkness was published by Arthur A. Levine Books in May. This sequel reveals why Balsa continues to roam as a spear-wielding warrior, and uncovers the mystery of her fierce past. The book has proved as popular a hit amongst adults in Japan as its predecessor. The book has also received a starred review on Publishers Weekly, a US industry magazine. <br /><br />\r\n<a href="http://www.publishersweekly.com/article/CA6653754.html" target="_blank">Publishers Weekly Children''s Book Reviews: Week of 27/4/2009</a>\r\n</p>\r\n\r\n<p style="float:right;"><a href="http://kaiseisha.net/overseas/fiction/country/title/479.html?country=13"><img src="http://www.kaiseisha.net/images/news/aug09/moribito.jpg" alt="MORIBITO II: Guardian of the Darkness" /></a></p>\r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n<!--//end of 1 //-->\r\n\r\n<h2 class="Clear"><a name="news02" id="news02"></a>100 Stories is going underground!</h2>\r\n<p class="Date">August 2009</p>\r\n<p>\r\n<table style="border-collapse:collapse; width:564px;">\r\n<tr>\r\n<td rowspan="3"><img src="http://www.kaiseisha.net/images/news/aug09/tokage.jpg" alt="100 Stories is going underground" /></td>\r\n<td colspan="2" style="height:199px; vertical-align:top; width:376px;">\r\nThe sequel to A House of 100 Stories, which was published in May 2008 and has already sold 180,000 copies…only this time, the stories go underground. A creature suddenly appears in Little Ku’s bathtub, and leads her underground to a world of adventure – populated by cute underground creatures such as hedgehogs, raccoons and lizards. Look out for the new title, scheduled for publishing in October this year.</td></tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td rowspan="2" style="vertical-align:bottom; width:208px;"><img src="http://www.kaiseisha.net/staging/images/news/aug09/tika100kai.jpg" /></td>\r\n<td  style="vertical-align:bottom; width:168px;">\r\n<a href="http://kaiseisha.net/backlist/picture/title/558.html"><img src="http://www.kaiseisha.net/images/news/aug09/100kaidatenoie.jpg" /></a></td>\r\n  </tr>\r\n  <tr>\r\n    \r\n    <td style="vertical-align:bottom;"><span class="NewsBookDescription"><a href="http://kaiseisha.net/staging/backlist/picture/title/558.html"><span class="NewsBookTitle">\r\n    A House of 100 Stories</span></a><br />\r\n	by Toshio Iwai<br />22 x 31 cm, 32 pages, Full-colour illustrations</span></td>\r\n  </tr>\r\n</table>\r\n</p>\r\n\r\n<!--//end of 2 //-->\r\n\r\n\r\n<h2 class="Clear"><a name="news03" id="news03"></a>A new addition to the Russian picture book series</h2>\r\n<p class="Date">August 2009</p>\r\n<p>A charming new addition to our original series of Russian picture books translated for a Japanese audience. The new publication is a collection of 22 of Russia’s traditional children’s folk songs, as selected by Kornei Chukovskii, one of the greats of Russia’s children’s literature. The songs are accompanied by illustrations, drawn in 1957 by IUrii Vasnetsov, which capture the atmosphere of the songs perfectly.\r\n</p>\r\n<table>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td><a href="http://kaiseisha.net/newpublications/newpicture/title/635.html"><img src="http://www.kaiseisha.net/images/news/aug09/russianowarabeuta.jpg" /></a></td>\r\n<td style="vertical-align:bottom; padding-left:10px;">\r\n<span class="NewsBookDescription"><span class="New">NEW!</span><span class="NewsBookTitle">Children’s Songs from Russia</span><br />\r\nedited by Kornei Chukovskii<br />translated by Kiyoshi Tanaka<br />illus. by IUrii Alekseevich Vasnetsov<br />\r\n29 x 25 cm, 32 pages, Full-colour illustrations</span>\r\n</td></tr></table>\r\n\r\n<p class="Clear">\r\n<table style="border-collapse:collapse; width:565px; margin-top:5px;">\r\n  <tr>\r\n    <td style="width:188px; vertical-align:bottom;">\r\n    <a href="http://kaiseisha.net/newpublications/newpicture/title/443.html">\r\n    <img src="http://www.kaiseisha.net/images/news/aug09/harinezumi.jpg" /></a></td>\r\n    <td style="width:188px; vertical-align:bottom;"><a href="http://kaiseisha.net/newpublications/newpicture/title/611.html"><img src="http://www.kaiseisha.net/images/news/aug09/gokiburi.jpg" /></a></td>\r\n    <td style="width:188px; vertical-align:bottom;">\r\n    <a href="http://kaiseisha.net/newpublications/newpicture/title/253.html"><img src="http://www.kaiseisha.net/images/news/aug09/wani.jpg" /></a></td>\r\n  </tr>\r\n  <tr>\r\n    <td style="vertical-align:top;"><span class="NewsBookDescription"><span class="NewsBookTitle">The Hedgehog and the Gold Coin</span><br />\r\nby Kiyoshi Tanaka<br />original story by Vladimir Orlov<br />illus. by Valentin Olshvang<br />\r\n27 x 21 cm, 32 pages, Full-colour illustrations</span></td>\r\n    <td style="vertical-align:top;"><span class="NewsBookDescription"><span class="NewsBookTitle">The Cockroach King</span><br />\r\nby Kornei Chukovskii<br />\r\ntranslated by Kiyoshi Tanaka<br />illus. by S. A. Ostrov<br />\r\n29 x 25 cm, 28 pages, Full-colour illustrations</span></td>\r\n    <td style="vertical-align:top;"><span class="NewsBookDescription"><span class="NewsBookTitle">What Happened to the Crocodile?</span><br />\r\nby Marina Moskvina<br />translated by Kiyoshi Tanaka<br />illus. by Valentin Olshvang<br />22 x 28 cm, 32 pages, Full-colour illustrations</span></td>\r\n  </tr>\r\n</table>\r\n</p>\r\n<!--//end of 3 //-->\r\n<h2><a name="news04" id="news04"></a>We will be exhibiting at the Beijing International Book Fair</h2>\r\n<p class="Date">August 2009</p>\r\n<p>The Beijing International Book Fair will be celebrating its 16th successful year in 2009, and is one of the most rapidly growing book fairs in the world. This year, the fair will held from 3rd – 7th September 2009. Kaisei-sha will be exhibiting, with a focus on books for reading and science learning books. We look forward to meeting and greeting you if you plan to attend the fair. \r\n</p>\r\n<p>\r\n<img src="http://www.kaiseisha.net/images/news/aug09/beijing01.jpg" alt="We will be appearing at the Beijing International Book Fair" />\r\n<img src="http://www.kaiseisha.net/images/news/aug09/beijing02.jpg" alt="We will be appearing at the Beijing International Book Fair" style=" margin-bottom:41px; margin-left:20px;" />\r\n</p>\r\n<!--//end of 4 //-->', '', 1, 1, 0, 1, '2009-09-08 02:33:48', 62, '', '2009-12-03 01:33:01', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2009-09-08 02:33:48', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', 'show_title=\nlink_titles=\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=\nshow_create_date=\nshow_modify_date=\nshow_pdf_icon=\nshow_print_icon=\nshow_email_icon=\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=', 2, 0, 25, '', '', 0, 709, 'robots=\nauthor='),
(16, 'November 2009', 'november2009', '', '<h2 class="TopItem"><a name="news01" id="news01"></a><a href="http://www.kaiseisha.net/newpublications/newpicture/title/665.html">Best-selling author of adult fiction writes first full-length children’s novel</a></h2>\r\n<p class="Date">November 2009</p>\r\n<p style="float:right;"><img src="http://www.kaiseisha.net/images/news/nov2009/snowy_2.jpg" width="165" height="248" ></p>\r\n<p><a href="http://www.kaiseisha.net/author/kaori_ekuni.html" target="_self">Kaori Ekuni</a> is an acclaimed author of fiction for adults, with a strong female fan base and particular support from younger women. Several of her novels have been adapted for the screen, and she is increasingly popular throughout Asia, in addition to her native Japan.\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n‘<a href="http://www.kaiseisha.net/newpublications/fiction/title/665.html">Snowy the Snowgirl</a>’ is Ekuni’s first full-length children’s story. Although Ekuni is widely associated with adult fiction, her debut publication was in fact a children’s story, and she has translated a number of picture book titles into Japanese.\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nMost of the time, snowpeople are made by children playing, rolling up the fallen snow into great bundles; but Snowy, the book’s main character, is, in fact, a wild snowgirl. One day, she came floating down from the skies, and started to live in the little house next to Yuriko, an artist. Going shopping, weighing herself, having supper with friends... everything is an adventure to Snowy, who is active, curious and full of joy. Elegant copperplate engravings by the renowned <a href="http://www.kaiseisha.net/illustrator/yoko_yamamoto.html" target="_self">Yoko Yamamoto</a> accompany the lyrical text.</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n<table>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td><a href="http://www.kaiseisha.net/newpublications/fiction/title/665.html" target="_self"><img src="http://www.kaiseisha.net/images/news/nov2009/snowy_1.jpg" width="198" height="283" border="0"></a></td>\r\n<td style="vertical-align:bottom; padding-left:10px;">\r\n<span class="NewsBookDescription"><span class="New">NEW!</span> <span class="NewsBookTitle">Snowy the Snowgirl</span><br />\r\nby Kaori Ekuni<br />\r\ncopperplate engravings by Yoko Yamamoto<br />\r\n20 x 14 cm, 234 pages<br />\r\nFull-colour illustrations</span></td>\r\n</tr></table>\r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n<!--//end of 1 //-->\r\n\r\n<h2 class="Clear"><a name="news02" id="news02"></a><a href="http://kaiseisha.net/backlist/picture/title/558.html">Giant book version of sell-out success story book on sale soon!</a></h2>\r\n<p class="Date">November 2009</p>\r\n<img src="http://www.kaiseisha.net/images/news/nov2009/big100.jpg" width="91" height="425" border="0" style="float:left; ">\r\n<p>After its initial publication in May 2008, ‘<a href="http://kaiseisha.net/backlist/picture/title/558.html">A House of 100 Stories</a>’ by <a href="http://www.kaiseisha.net/author/toshio_iwai.html" target="_self">Toshio Iwai</a>, has built up a strong following, and has sold a massive 200,000 copies to date.  And now, a giant-sized edition of the hit book is about to be released!\r\n<br />\r\nIn the original version, readers flipped the pages from the bottom to the top of the book, but in this new giant-book version, readers flip the pages of the book, which measures a massive 120cm in length, from left to right. Children are sure to be excited and entranced a book that’s even bigger than they are!\r\n<br />\r\nNext month also sees the publication of ‘An Underground House of 100 Stories’. The 100 Stories series is certainly shaping up into something very exciting indeed!</p>\r\n<p><img src="images/news/nov2009/big100_B.jpg" width="416" height="286" style="margin-right:10px;"></p>\r\n <p><span class="NewsBookDescription"><span class="New">NEW!</span>  <span class="NewsBookTitle">Giant Book: A House of 100 Stories</span><br />\r\nby Toshio Iwai<br />\r\n120 × 20 cm, 34 pages<br />\r\nFull-colour illustrations</span></p>\r\n\r\n<!--//end of 2 //-->\r\n<h2 class="Clear"><a name="news03" id="news03"></a><a href="http://www.kaiseisha.net/newpublications/fiction/title/665.html">A Giraffe, a Whale, a Fur Seal... and now a Sea Otter!</a></h2>\r\n<p class="Date">November 2009</p>\r\n<p>This charming series of books brings together different animals through the medium of letters; their correspondence eventually leads to fun meetings and deep friendships.\r\n\r\nFollowing on from ‘<a href="http://www.kaiseisha.net/backlist/fiction/title/110.html">I’m an African Giraffe</a>’, ‘<a href="http://www.kaiseisha.net/backlist/fiction/title/111.html">The Whale that lives at Cape Whale</a>’ and ‘<a href="http://www.kaiseisha.net/backlist/fiction/title/112.html">How are you, Fur Seal</a>’, three immensely popular titles, comes ‘<a href="http://www.kaiseisha.net/newpublications/fiction/title/665.html">My name is Drifter, from the Seaweed Forest</a>’.\r\n\r\nIn this new episode, Drifter, a sea otter living in the Seaweed Forest, is visited by Sheldon, a travelling turtle. Every day, Sheldon leaves the Seaweed Forest, carrying his great big bag, and whenever something happens, he whips out his notepad and starts to scribble.\r\n\r\nOne day, calm in the Seaweed Forest is disturbed by a robbery! And it seems that Sheldon is the suspect, but what else is he hiding…?\r\n</p>\r\n<table>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td><a href="http://www.kaiseisha.net/newpublications/fiction/title/664.html" target="_self"><img src="http://www.kaiseisha.net/images/news/nov2009/pukapuka_1.jpg" width="198" height="276" border="0" /></a></td>\r\n<td style="vertical-align:bottom; padding-left:10px;">\r\n<span class="NewsBookDescription"><span class="New">NEW!</span>\r\n<span class="NewsBookTitle">My name is Drifter, from the Seaweed Forest</span><br />\r\n by Megumi Iwasa<br />\r\n illus. by Jun Takabatake<br />\r\n22 x 16 cm, 106 pages<br />\r\nBlack-and-white illustrations</span>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr></table>\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<table border="0" cellpadding="0">\r\n  <tr>\r\n    <td><a href="http://www.kaiseisha.net/backlist/fiction/title/110.html" target="_self"><img src="http://www.kaiseisha.net/images/news/nov2009/pukapuka_2.jpg" width="150" height="212" border="0" style="margin-right:35px;"></a></td>\r\n    <td><a href="http://www.kaiseisha.net/backlist/fiction/title/111.html" target="_self"><img src="http://www.kaiseisha.net/images/news/nov2009/pukapuka_3.jpg" width="150" height="214" border="0" style="margin-right:35px;" ></a></td>\r\n    <td><a href="http://www.kaiseisha.net/backlist/fiction/title/112.html" target="_self"><img src="http://www.kaiseisha.net/images/news/nov2009/pukapuka_4.jpg" width="150" height="214" border="0"></a></td>\r\n  </tr>\r\n  <tr>\r\n    <td valign="top"><img src="http://www.kaiseisha.net/images/news/nov2009/cl_2.gif" width="5" height="5"><br />\r\n	<span class="NewsBookDescription"><span class="NewsBookTitle">I''m an African Giraffe</span><br />\r\n by Megumi Iwasa<br />\r\n illus. by Jun Takabatake<br />\r\n22 x 16 cm, 102 pages<br />\r\nBlack-and-white illustrations</span></td>\r\n    <td valign="top"><img src="http://www.kaiseisha.net/images/news/nov2009/cl_2.gif" width="5" height="5"><br />\r\n<span class="NewsBookDescription">\r\n	<span class="NewsBookTitle">The Whale that Lived \r\n	<br />at Cape Whale</span><br />\r\nby Megumi Iwasa<br />\r\nillus. by Jun Takabatake<br />\r\n22 x 16 cm, 102 pages<br />\r\nBlack-and-white illustrations</span></td>\r\n    <td valign="top"><img src="http://www.kaiseisha.net/images/news/nov2009/cl_2.gif" width="5" height="5"><br />\r\n<span class="NewsBookDescription"><span class="NewsBookTitle">How are You, Fur Seal?</span><br />\r\nby Megumi Iwasa<br />\r\nillus. by Jun Takabatake<br />\r\n22 x 16 cm, 102 pages<br />\r\nBlack-and-white illustrations</span></td>\r\n  </tr>\r\n</table>\r\n<p class="Clear">\r\n</p>\r\n<!--//end of 3 //-->', '', 1, 1, 0, 1, '2009-11-29 14:35:02', 62, '', '2009-12-03 01:36:15', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2009-11-29 14:35:02', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', 'show_title=\nlink_titles=\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=\nshow_create_date=\nshow_modify_date=\nshow_pdf_icon=\nshow_print_icon=\nshow_email_icon=\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=', 7, 0, 24, '', '', 0, 779, 'robots=\nauthor='),
(17, 'February 2010', 'february-2010', '', '<h2 class="TopItem"><a name="news01" id="news01"></a>Kaisei-sha to exhibit at Bologna Children’s Book Fair 2010</h2>\r\n<p class="Date">February 2010</p>\r\n<p>Kaisei-sha is delighted to be once again exhibiting at the Bologna Children’s Book Fair, which will be held in Bologna, Italy between 23rd and 26th March. Please do pop along and visit us if you have time, you can find us in Hall 29 A18.\r\nWe’ve also completed our <a href="images/news/feb2010/2010_Catalogue.pdf" target="_blank">Foreign Rights Catalogue 2010</a> in time for the Book Fair. The catalogue showcases around 90 titles, with a focus on new titles. We’ll be distributing the catalogue at the Book Fair, so make sure to pick up your copy. If you can''t make it to the Book Fair, you can still get your hands on a copy by downloading it via the link at the top of the page.\r\n</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n<table>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td><img src="images/news/feb2010/RIMG0056.jpg" width="224" height="230" border="0"></td>\r\n<td style="vertical-align:bottom; padding-left:10px;"><a href="images/news/feb2010/2010_Catalogue.pdf" target="_blank"><img src="images/news/feb2010/catalogue.jpg" alt="catalogue" width="325" height="230" border="0"></a></td>\r\n</tr></table>\r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n<!--//end of 1 //-->\r\n\r\n<h2 class="Clear"><a name="news02" id="news02"></a><a href="http://www.kaiseisha.net/overseas/fiction/country/title/480.html?country=13">MORIBITO II: Guardian of the Darkness awarded a Mildred L. Batchelder Honor 2010.</a></h2>\r\n<p class="Date">February 2010 </p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href="http://www.kaiseisha.net/author/nahoko_uehashi.html" target="_self">Nahoko Uehashi</a>’s ‘<a href="http://www.kaiseisha.net/overseas/fiction/country/title/480.html?country=13" target="_self">MORIBITO II: Guardian of the Darkness</a>’, as translated into English by Cathy Hiroano and published in 2009 by Arthur A. Levine Books, has been awarded the Mildred L. Batchelder Honor 2010.\r\nThe Mildred L. Batchelder Award, established in 1966, is a citation awarded annually to an American publisher for a children''s book considered to be the most outstanding of those books originally published in a foreign language in a foreign country, and subsequently translated into English and published in the United States. The Honors are awarded simultaneously to three other outstanding books.\r\nThis is the second triumph in two years for the exceptional MORIBITO series; last year, ‘<a href="http://www.kaiseisha.net/overseas/fiction/country/title/479.html?country=13" target="_self">MORIBITO: Guardian of the Spirit</a>’, also translated by Cathy Hirano, won the Mildred L. Batchelder Award.\r\n</p>\r\n<p><a href="http://www.ala.org/ala/mgrps/divs/alsc/awardsgrants/bookmedia/batchelderaward/index.cfm" target="_blank">American Library Association</a></p>\r\n<table>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p><a href="http://www.kaiseisha.net/overseas/fiction/country/title/480.html?country=13" target="_self"><img src="images/news/feb2010/guardiandarkness_US.jpg" width="167" height="250" border="0" style="margin-right:10px;"></a></p></td>\r\n<td valign="bottom"> <p><span class="NewsBookDescription"><span class="NewsBookTitle">MORIBITO (Guardian)<br />\r\nGuardian of the Dark</span><br />\r\nby Nahoko Uehashi<br />\r\nillus. by Makiko Futaki<br />\r\n22 x 16 cm, 284-359 pages<br />\r\nBlack-and-white illustrations</span></p></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<!--//end of 2 //-->\r\n<h2 class="Clear"><a name="news03" id="news03"></a><a href="http://www.kaiseisha.net/newpublications/newpicture/title/672.html" target="_self">An Underground House of 100 Stories</a> close to selling its 200,000th copy whilst <a href="http://www.kaiseisha.net/backlist/picture/title/558.html" target="_self">A House of 100 Stories</a> reaches the 350,000 mark!</h2>\r\n<p class="Date">February 2010 </p>\r\n<p>‘<a href="http://www.kaiseisha.net/newpublications/newpicture/title/672.html" target="_self">An Underground House of 100 Stories</a>’, the follow-up to the smash success of ‘<a href="http://www.kaiseisha.net/backlist/picture/title/558.html" target="_self">A House of 100 Stories</a>’, was first published in November 2009. In just three months, the book has sold an incredible 180,000+ copies.<br />\r\nSuch roaring success is the exception rather than the rule in the children’s book industry. Its popularity is thanks to a successful Christmas season and the influence of its predecessor, ‘<a href="http://www.kaiseisha.net/backlist/picture/title/558.html" target="_self">A House of 100 Stories</a>’, which has reached the 350,000 mark since being published in March 2008.<br />\r\nForeign rights have been sold to China, Korea and Taiwan, with the book apparently doing particularly well in Taiwan.<br />\r\n</p>\r\n<table>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td><a href="http://www.kaiseisha.net/backlist/picture/title/558.html" target="_self"><img src="images/news/feb2010/100_house.jpg" alt="100 house" width="179" height="250" border="0" style="margin-right:10px;"></a>\r\n</td>\r\n<td><a href="http://www.kaiseisha.net/newpublications/newpicture/title/672.html" target="_self"><img src="images/news/feb2010/100th_underground.jpg" width="178" height="250" border="0" /></a></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n  <td><span class="NewsBookDescription"><span class="NewsBookTitle">A House of 100 Stories</span><br />\r\n by Toshio Iwai <br />\r\n\r\n22 x 31 cm, 32 pages<br />\r\nFull-colour illustrations</span></td>\r\n  <td><span class="NewsBookDescription"><span class="New">NEW!</span>\r\n<span class="NewsBookTitle">An Underground House of 100 Stories</span><br />\r\n by Toshio Iwai <br />\r\n\r\n22 x 31 cm, 32 pages<br />\r\nFull-colour illustrations</span></td>\r\n  </tr>\r\n</table>\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n<p class="Clear">\r\n</p>\r\n<!--//end of 3 //-->', '', 1, 1, 0, 1, '2010-03-11 15:31:43', 62, '', '2010-03-11 16:28:01', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2010-03-11 15:31:43', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', 'show_title=\nlink_titles=\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=\nshow_create_date=\nshow_modify_date=\nshow_pdf_icon=\nshow_print_icon=\nshow_email_icon=\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=', 2, 0, 23, '', '', 0, 590, 'robots=\nauthor=');
