(29, 'February 2013', 'feb2013', '', '<h2 class="TopItem"><a name="news01" id="news01"></a>More Counting to 100—This Time with Monkeys! </h2>\r\n<p class="Date">February 2013 </p>\r\n<p>There has been a brand new addition to the perennially popular “100” series by <a href="http://www.kaiseisha.net/author/masayuki_sebe.html" target="_self">Masayuki Sebe</a>, already published in 12 countries worldwide. Until now, the series has been focused on finding and counting, but "<a href="http://www.kaiseisha.net/newpublications/newpicture/title/825.html" target="_self">Find Them All! 100 Monkeys</a>" tells the story of 100 very hungry, very cheeky monkeys, who all set off in search of something tasty to eat. Although they find themselves being chased by a terrifying monster, in the end, they all manage to make friends; it’s a heart-warming story that young readers will love. The book allows children to enjoy counting while listening to the exciting tale of the hungry monkeys. The perfect way to read, count and have fun together. </p>\r\n\r\n<table>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td><a href="http://www.kaiseisha.net/newpublications/newpicture/title/825.html"><img src="images/news/feb2013/100monkeys.jpg" alt="Find Them All! 100 Monkeys" width="174" height="211" border="0" style="margin-right:10px;"></a></td>\r\n<td><img src="images/news/feb2013/100monkeys2.jpg" width="345" height="211"></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td valign="top">\r\n<span class="NewsBookDescription">\r\n <span class="NewsBookTitle">Find Them All! 100 Monkeys</span><br />\r\nby Masayuki Sebe<br />\r\n26 x 21 cm, 24 pages<br />\r\nFull-colour illustrations</span></td>\r\n <td valign="top"></td>\r\n\r\n</tr>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<h2 class="TopItem"><a name="news02" id="news02"></a>“Hot” New Picture Book from <a href="http://www.kaiseisha.net/author/satoshi_kitamura.html" target="_self">Satoshi Kitamura</a></h2>\r\n<p class="Date">February 2013</p>\r\n<p><a href="http://www.kaiseisha.net/author/satoshi_kitamura.html" target="_self">Satoshi Kitamura</a> is a picture book author and illustrator previously based in the UK. Kaisei-sha is delighted to announce publication of the first picture book Satoshi has ever developed originally in Japanese. Satoshi lived in the UK for an extended period, during which time his illustrations were featured in books published by Andersen Press and many other esteemed publishing houses worldwide. In this brand new book, the main character is a little girl’s hot water bag. Unable to bear one more night squished between the little girl’s cold feet, the hot water bag makes its escape from her bed, flying away between buildings, across the desert, beyond the ends of the Earth, all the way to outer space. Will the little girl ever be able to warm her feet on her favourite hot water bag again? The only way to find out is to read the book. </p>\r\n<table>\r\n  <tr>\r\n    <td width="247"> <a href="http://www.kaiseisha.net/newpublications/newpicture/title/822.html" target="_self"><img src="images/news/feb2013/yutanpo.jpg" alt="My Sweet Hot Water Bag" width="237" height="211" border="0" style="margin:0 10px 0 0;"></a></td>\r\n    <td width="294" valign="bottom"><span class="NewsBookDescription"><span class="NewsBookTitle">My Sweet Hot Water Bag</span><br />\r\nby Satoshi Kitamura<br />\r\n18 x 20 cm, 46 pages<br />\r\nFull-colour illustrations </span> </td>\r\n  </tr>\r\n  <tr>\r\n    <td valign="top" colspan="2"> <span class="NewsBookDescription"><img src="images/news/feb2013/yutanpo2.jpg" alt="My Sweet Hot Water Bag" width="479" height="211" border="0" style="margin-top:10px; "></a> </span></td>\r\n   \r\n  </tr>\r\n</table>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h2 class="TopItem"><a name="news03" id="news03"></a>Sequels to <a href="http://www.kaiseisha.net/backlist/picture/title/120.html" target="_self">Mr. Crow’s Bakery</a> 40 Years since its Release</h2>\r\n<p class="Date">February 2013</p>\r\n<p>This year will be the fortieth year since the release of <a href="http://www.kaiseisha.net/backlist/picture/title/120.html" target="_self">Mr Crow’s Bakery</a> in 1973. Since it first went on sale, the book has been read and loved by many children and adults alike, selling an amazing 2.1 million copies. The four little chicks that were born to Mr. Crow, and who helped Mr. and Mrs. Crow to run their bakery in the first book, are now all grown up. To celebrate the fortieth anniversary of the book, four new stories are being published simultaneously, with each book following the fortunes of one of the four chicks, from opening their businesses (between them they run a sweet shop, a grocer’s, a tempura store and a noodle shop) to starting their own families. In the spirit of the original, each book is jam-packed with delicious illustrations of dishes, real-life enough to make your mouth water. </p>\r\n\r\n<table width="522" border="0" cellspacing="10" cellpadding="0">\r\n  <tr>\r\n    <td><a href="http://www.kaiseisha.net/backlist/picture/title/120.html" target="_self"><img src="images/news/feb2013/crow_bakery.jpg" width="172" height="211" border="1"></a></td>\r\n    <td><img src="images/news/feb2013/crow_okashi.jpg" width="174" height="211" border="1"></td>\r\n    <td><img src="images/news/feb2013/crow_yaoya.jpg" width="174" height="211" border="1"></td>\r\n  </tr>\r\n\r\n  <tr>\r\n    <td><img src="images/news/feb2013/crow_tempra.jpg" width="174" height="211" border="1"></td>\r\n    <td><img src="images/news/feb2013/crow_soba.jpg" width="173" height="211" border="1"></td>\r\n    <td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n  </tr>\r\n</table>\r\n<br />\r\n<h2 class="TopItem"><a name="news04" id="news04"></a>\r\n\r\nKaisei-sha Featured in PW</h2>\r\n<p class="Date">February 2013</p>\r\n<p>Kaisei-sha has been featured in PW, or Publishers Weekly, an industry news magazine published in the US and focused on the international book publishing business. The January 21 2013 issue featured an article entitled Children’s Publishing in Asia 2012: A Mix of Translations, Originals, E-books, and Apps, in which Kaisei-sha was mentioned. The article talks about the success of foreign rights sales for Japanese children’s literature as well as some exciting new Kaisei-sha titles. Please do take a look—the article is available online via the following link: <br />\r\n  <a href="http://www.publishersweekly.com/pw/by-topic/childrens/childrens-industry-news/feb2013/article/55557-children-s-publishing-in-asia-2012-a-mix-of-translations-originals-e-books-and-apps.html" target="_blank">http://www.publishersweekly.com/pw/by-topic/childrens/childrens-industry-news/feb2013/article/55557-children-s-publishing-in-asia-2012-a-mix-of-translations-originals-e-books-and-apps.html</a></p>\r\n<br />\r\n<h2 class="TopItem"><a name="news05" id="news04"></a>\r\n\r\nKaisei-sha to Exhibit at the 50th Bologna Children’s Book Fair</h2>\r\n<p class="Date">February 2013</p>\r\n<p>The Bologna Children’s Book Fair is 50 years old this year, and Kaisei-sha will be attending to help celebrate a half century of success. Kaisei-sha was among the first Japanese publishers to become a presence at the Bologna Children’s Book Fair; we have been attending over the past 40 years. We’ll be back in the same place—Hall 29, A18—and we look forward to seeing as many of you as possible at this year’s extra special fair. </p>\r\n<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0">\r\n  <tr>\r\n    <td><img src="images/news/feb2013/bologna.jpg" width="179" height="211" style="margin-right:10px; "></td>\r\n    <td><img src="images/news/feb2013/bologna2.jpg" width="284" height="211"></td>\r\n  </tr>\r\n</table>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', '', 1, 1, 0, 1, '2013-03-19 21:57:32', 62, '', '2013-03-19 22:14:24', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2013-03-19 21:57:32', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', 'show_title=\nlink_titles=\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=\nshow_create_date=\nshow_modify_date=\nshow_pdf_icon=\nshow_print_icon=\nshow_email_icon=\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=', 7, 0, 11, '', '', 0, 677, 'robots=\nauthor='),
(30, 'May 2013', 'may2013', '', '<h2 class="TopItem"><a name="news01" id="news01"></a>Now, a Big Princess! Prequel to Internationally Renowned ‘<a href="http://www.kaiseisha.net/backlist/picture/title/702.html" target="_self">The Tiny King</a>’</h2>\r\n<p class="Date">May 2013 </p>\r\n<p>‘<a href="http://www.kaiseisha.net/backlist/picture/title/702.html" target="_self">The Tiny King</a>’, by <a href="http://www.kaiseisha.net/author/taro_miura.html" target="_self">Taro Miura</a>, was a tale of a Tiny King who left his lonely life behind when he married a Big Princess. This happy tale, told with bold graphic illustrations, was an instant hit at home—it won a prize at the Sankei Children’s Publishing Culture Awards, one of Japan’s most prestigious prizes for children’s literature—and overseas, with versions already translated into and published in English, French, Spanish, Korean, Chinese, and Taiwanese Mandarin. </p>\r\n\r\n<p>This new book in the series takes a look at how the Big Princess got so big, making it a prequel to the events in ‘<a href="http://www.kaiseisha.net/backlist/picture/title/702.html" target="_self">The Tiny King</a>’. It was published in Japan in June 2013.</p>\r\n<p>One day, in the garden of their castle, a King and Queen find a tiny princess, but she grows bigger and bigger every day! Soon, she’s so big that she can hardly fit into the castle. Some of the pages feature fold-out sections, bringing <a href="http://www.kaiseisha.net/author/taro_miura.html" target="_self">Taro Miura</a>’s unique and dynamic approach to illustration to life even more vibrantly. </p>\r\n<p>Perhaps the next book will reveal more about the children born to the Tiny King and the Big Princess? It’s certainly something to look forward to! </p>\r\n\r\n<table>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td><a href="http://www.kaiseisha.net/backlist/fiction/title/859.html" target="_self"><img src="images/news/may2013/big_princess.jpg" alt="The Big Princess" width="122" height="211" border="0" style="margin-right:10px; margin-bottom:5px;"></td>\r\n<td><img src="images/news/may2013/big_princess2.jpg" width="306" height="211" border="0" style="margin-right:10px; margin-bottom:5px;"></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td valign="top">\r\n\r\n<span class="NewsBookDescription"><span class="NewsBookTitle">The Big Princess</span><br />\r\nby Taro Miura <br />\r\n31 x 18 cm, 34 pages<br />\r\nFull-colour illustrations</span></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<br />\r\n<h2 class="TopItem"><a name="news02" id="news02"></a>Two Kaisei-sha Publications Win at the Sankei Children’s Publishing Culture Awards</h2>\r\n<p class="Date">May 2013</p>\r\n<p>In 2011, ‘<a href="http://www.kaiseisha.net/backlist/picture/title/702.html" target="_self">The Tiny King</a>’ won the Achievement in Art Direction prize at the Sankei Children’s Publishing Culture Awards, and this year two more Kaisei-sha publications have been honoured: ‘<a href="http://www.kaiseisha.net/backlist/picture/title/799.html" target="_self">A Sudden Evening Shower</a>’, by <a href="http://www.kaiseisha.net/author/bingo_aki.html" target="_self">Bingo Aki</a>, has won the JR Prize, while ‘<a href="http://www.kaiseisha.net/backlist/fiction/title/800.html" target="_self">The Corner Where Dreams Come True</a>’, by <a href="http://www.kaiseisha.net/author/jun_okada.html">Jun Okada</a>, has won the Fuji Television Prize. </p>\r\n<p>‘<a href="http://www.kaiseisha.net/backlist/picture/title/799.html" target="_self">A Sudden Evening Shower</a>’ was inspired by a traditional story from Trinidad and Tobago; <a href="http://www.kaiseisha.net/author/bingo_aki.html" target="_self">Bingo Aki</a>’s version has been brought to life with illustrations rooted in traditional Japanese artistic techniques, rendered in beautifully vivid colours. The sing-off between the wolf and the goat, his unexpected guest, is a tale not to be missed. </p>\r\n<p>‘<a href="http://www.kaiseisha.net/backlist/fiction/title/800.html" target="_self">The Corner Where Dreams Come True</a>’ is a collection of stories told by a beloved grandpa, although sometimes they seem too fantastic to be true—could granny really have been a thunderstorm princess? </p>\r\n<p>These prizes will hopefully lead many more readers to these two outstanding publications. </p>\r\n\r\n<table>\r\n <tr>\r\n <td width="170" valign="bottom"> <a href="http://www.kaiseisha.net/backlist/fiction/title/799.html" target="_self"><img src="images/news/may2013/yudachi.jpg" alt="The Sudden Evening Shower" width="150" height="184" border="0" style="margin-right:25px; margin-bottom:5px;"></a></a></td>\r\n\r\n <td width="190" valign="bottom"><a href="http://www.kaiseisha.net/backlist/fiction/title/800.html" target="_self"><img src="images/news/may2013/negai.jpg" alt="The Corner Where Dreams Come True" width="150" height="213" border="0" style="margin-right:10px; margin-bottom:5px;"></a></a></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n    <td width="170" valign="top"><span class="NewsBookDescription"><span class="NewsBookTitle">A Sudden Evening Shower</span><br />\r\nby Bingo Aki<br />\r\n26 x 22 cm, 32 pages<br />\r\nFull-colour illustrations </span> </td>\r\n <td width="170" valign="bottom"><span class="NewsBookDescription"><span class="NewsBookTitle">The Corner Where Dreams Come True</span><br />\r\nby Jun Okada<br />\r\nillus. by Rokudai Tanaka<br />\r\n22 x 16 cm, 126 pages<br />\r\nBlack-and-white illustrations</span> </td>\r\n  </tr>\r\n</table>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<h2 class="TopItem"><a name="news03" id="news03"></a>‘<a href="http://www.kaiseisha.net/backlist/picture/title/808.html" target="_self">Little Hanna</a>’ Published Internationally</h2>\r\n<p class="Date">May 2013</p>\r\n<p><a href="http://www.kaiseisha.net/author/komako_sakai.html">Komako Sakai</a>’s new picture book, <a href="http://www.kaiseisha.net/staging/backlist/picture/title/822.html">‘Little Hanna’</a>, has been published in a number of countries around the world. </p>\r\n<p>In this charming tale, little Hanna wakes up in the middle of the night, and explores the quiet of the house, eating cherries and playing with her sister’s toys. There is something nostalgic and timeless about the story itself, complemented by the delicate warmth of <a href="http://www.kaiseisha.net/author/komako_sakai.html">Sakai</a>’s illustrations, which encourage a sense of empathy and closeness with Hanna. </p>\r\n<p>Versions in English, French, Spanish, German, Italian, and Dutch are already underway. Publication dates are pending, but definitely something to look forward to!</p>\r\n<table>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td><a href="http://www.kaiseisha.net/backlist/picture/title/808.html" target="_self"><img src="images/news/may2013/hanna.jpg" alt="Little Hanna" width="150" height="181" border="0" style="margin-right:10px; margin-bottom:5px"></a></td>\r\n  </tr>\r\n  <tr>\r\n<td valign="top">\r\n  <span class="NewsBookDescription"><span class="NewsBookTitle">Little Hanna</span><br />\r\nby Komako Sakai <br />\r\n26 x 22 cm, 32 pages<br />\r\nFull-colour illustrations </span></td>\r\n</tr></table>\r\n<br /><br />\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<h2 class="TopItem"><a name="news04" id="news04"></a>Sequels to ‘<a href="http://www.kaiseisha.net/newpublications/newpicture/title/120.html" target="_self">Mr. Crow’s Bakery</a>’ Prove Hugely Popular</h2>\r\n<p class="Date">May 2013</p>\r\n<p>‘<a href="http://www.kaiseisha.net/newpublications/newpicture/title/120.html" target="_self">Mr. Crow’s Bakery</a>’ was first published back in 1973 and has sold 2.1 million copies since that first edition was made available. Four new stories were published this spring, two in April and two in May, and the combined sales total for these four titles has already exceeded 400,000 units. </p>\r\n\r\n<p>Each book tells the story of one of Mr. Crow’s chicks, who go on to open, variously, a sweet shop, a grocer’s, a tempura store and a noodle shop, and eventually start their own families, too. </p>\r\n<p>The books have proved a hit with grown-ups who remember reading ‘<a href="http://www.kaiseisha.net/newpublications/newpicture/title/120.html" target="_self">Mr. Crow’s Bakery</a>’ as children, as well as the new generation of children who fell in love with Mr. Crow. It seems that ‘<a href="http://www.kaiseisha.net/newpublications/newpicture/title/120.html" target="_self">Mr. Crow’s Bakery</a>’ is busier than ever. </p>\r\n<table width="580" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0">\r\n  <tr>\r\n    <td width="145px"><a href="http://www.kaiseisha.net/newpublications/newpicture/title/844.html" target="_self"><img src="images/news/may2013/crow_okashi.jpg" alt="Chocco Crow" width="120" height="146" border="0" style="margin-bottom:5px;"></a></td>\r\n    <td width="145px"><a href="http://www.kaiseisha.net/newpublications/newpicture/title/843.html" target="_self"><img src="images/news/may2013/crow_yaoya.jpg" alt="Grocery" width="120" height="146" border="0" style="margin-bottom:5px;"></a></td>\r\n    <td width="145px"><a href="http://www.kaiseisha.net/newpublications/newpicture/title/845.html" target="_self"><img src="images/news/may2013/crow_tempra.jpg" alt="Tempra" width="120" height="146" border="0" style="margin-bottom:5px;"></a></td>\r\n    <td width="145px"><a href="http://www.kaiseisha.net/newpublications/newpicture/title/846.html" target="_self"><img src="images/news/may2013/crow_soba.jpg" alt="Soba" width="120" height="146" border="0" style="margin-bottom:5px;"></a></td>\r\n  </tr>\r\n  <tr>\r\n    <td valign="top"><span class="NewsBookDescription"><span class="NewsBookTitle">Chocco Crow''s Sweet Shop</span><br />\r\nby Satoshi Kako <br />\r\n26 x 21 cm, 32 pages<br />\r\nFull-colour illustrations </span></td>\r\n    <td valign="top"><span class="NewsBookDescription"><span class="NewsBookTitle">Apple Crow''s Grocery</span><br />\r\nby Satoshi Kako <br />\r\n26 x 21 cm, 32 pages<br />\r\nFull-colour illustrations </span></td>\r\n    <td valign="top"><span class="NewsBookDescription"><span class="NewsBookTitle">Lemon Crow''s Tempura Store</span><br />\r\nby Satoshi Kako <br />\r\n26 x 21 cm, 32 pages<br />\r\nFull-colour illustrations </span></td>\r\n    <td valign="top"><span class="NewsBookDescription"><span class="NewsBookTitle">Snowy Crow''s Noodle Shop</span><br />\r\nby Satoshi Kako <br />\r\n26 x 21 cm, 32 pages<br />\r\nFull-colour illustrations </span></td>\r\n  </tr>\r\n</table>\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<h2 class="TopItem"><a name="news05" id="news05"></a><a href="http://www.kaiseisha.net/author/nahoko_uehashi.html">Nanako Uehashi</a> on Author’s Award Shortlist for the Hans Christian Andersen Awards 2014</h2>\r\n<p class="Date">May 2013</p>\r\n<p><a href="http://www.kaiseisha.net/author/nahoko_uehashi.html">Nanako Uehashi</a> is on the Author’s Award shortlist for the Hans Christian Andersen Awards 2014. </p>\r\n<p><a href="http://www.kaiseisha.net/author/nahoko_uehashi.html">Nanako</a> is well-known for her globally popular series, MORIBITO, which has been translated into English, Italian, Spanish, Portuguese, French, Chinese, and Taiwanese Mandarin, among others. In 2009, the English translation of ‘MORIBITO: Guardian of the Spirit (Arthur A. Levine Books/Scholastic)’ won the Mildred L. Batchelder Award, given to the most outstanding children’s book originally published in a language other than English. The following year, ‘MORIBITO II: Guardian of the Dark’ was awarded Honors in the same Award, highlighting the extent to which this series is renowned overseas. The Hans Christian Andersen Awards will be announced at next year at the Bologna Children’s Book Fair. Something else to look forward to and a great excuse to re-read the series. </p>\r\n<table>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td><img src="images/news/may2013/uehashi.jpg" alt="Little Hanna" width="150" height="226" border="0" style="margin-right:10px;"></a></td>\r\n </tr>\r\n</table>\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<h2 class="TopItem"><a name="news06" id="news06"></a>New Book in the Popular Rent-a-Ghost Series</h2>\r\n<p class="Date">May 2013</p>\r\n<p>Tamotsu is an elementary school kid with a difference—he also runs the local Rent-a-Ghost store. This book is the third in this popular series, bringing together a menagerie of cute and cuddly ghosts overseen by the hardworking Tamotsu. This time around, one of Tamotsu’s ghosts ends up posing for a portrait! It’s great fun to read and to discover the new friends that Tamotsu and his ghosts are making. </p>\r\n<p>The book also features mini comic strips and lots of devices to make sure little readers don’t get bored sitting still to read! </p>\r\n<table width="540" border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0">\r\n  <tr>\r\n    <td width="180px" valign="top"><a href="http://www.kaiseisha.net/backlist/fiction/title/759.html"><img src="images/news/may2013/obake1.jpg" alt="What Ghosts Do For a Living" width="150" height="200" border="0" style="margin-right:25px; margin-bottom:5px; "></a></td>\r\n    <td width="180px" valign="top"><a href="http://www.kaiseisha.net/backlist/fiction/title/796.html" target="_self"><img src="images/news/may2013/obake2.jpg" width="150" height="200" border="0" style="margin-right:25px; margin-bottom:5px; "></a></td>\r\n    <td width="180px" valign="top"><a href="http://www.kaiseisha.net/newpublications/fiction/title/850.html" target="_self"><img src="images/news/may2013/obake3.jpg" alt="What Ghosts Do For a Living" width="150" height="200" border="0" style="margin-right:25px; margin-bottom:5px; "></a></td>\r\n  </tr>\r\n  <tr>\r\n    <td width="180px"><span class="NewsBookDescription"><span class="NewsBookTitle">What Ghosts Do For a Living</span><br />\r\nby Rika Okabe<br />\r\n21 x 16 cm, 87 pages<br />\r\nFull-colour and black-and-white<br />illustrations</span></td>\r\n    <td><span class="NewsBookDescription"><span class="NewsBookTitle">Trust Us with Your Secret Tasks</span><br />\r\nby Rika Okabe<br />\r\n21 x 16 cm, 87 pages<br />\r\nFull-colour and black-and-white <br />illustrations</span></td>\r\n    <td valign="top"><span class="NewsBookDescription"><span class="NewsBookTitle">What Ghosts Do For a Living</span><br />\r\nby Rika Okabe<br />\r\n21 x 16 cm, 87 pages<br />\r\nFull-colour and black-and-white</span></td>\r\n  </tr>\r\n</table>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', '', 1, 1, 0, 1, '2013-06-27 00:31:44', 62, '', '2013-07-10 12:49:11', 62, 0, '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '2013-06-27 00:31:44', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', '', 'show_title=\nlink_titles=\nshow_intro=\nshow_section=\nlink_section=\nshow_category=\nlink_category=\nshow_vote=\nshow_author=\nshow_create_date=\nshow_modify_date=\nshow_pdf_icon=\nshow_print_icon=\nshow_email_icon=\nlanguage=\nkeyref=\nreadmore=', 46, 0, 10, '', '', 0, 552, 'robots=\nauthor='),
(33, 'February 2014', 'feb2014', '', '<h2 class="TopItem"><a name="news01" id="news01"></a>\r\nFriends Around the World: Exciting New Series Kicks Off With Initial Volumes </h2>\r\n<p class="Date">February 2014</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In 2016, Kaisei-sha will celebrate 80 years since its establishment, and we have decided to mark the occasion with a very special 36-volume series, "Friends Around the World", to be published between now and 2016. </p>\r\n<p>Each volume contains photography and text focused on one child living with a family resident in the featured country. The photographer spends time with the child and his or her family, gathering images of everyday life, such as going to school, traditional events, and leisure time. The text, written by the photographer, is carefully crafted in simple language to accompany the photography and paint its own vivid picture of the life of the child, wherever he or she may be. To the end of each volume, the history, politics, industry and other key facts of the featured country are introduced, to encourage greater understanding. </p>\r\n<p>The spread of the internet has globalised our world, making it so much smaller and bringing people much closer together. Still, however, the ordinary lives of children in other countries are often unfamiliar, even unknown, to us. This series presents the everyday joy that is present in the lives of children all over the world. </p>\r\n<p>The photographers taking part in this series include multiple-award winning photojournalists who have spent many years living with and photographing their subjects, as well as young artists using photography as their chosen medium. </p>\r\n<p>The series as it is currently planned is outlined below—is your country included? This series is a wonderful opportunity to travel the world through the eyes of its children. </p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Series One: 12 volumes</b></p>\r\n<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0">\r\n  <tr>\r\n    <td valign="top" width="120" s